<li class="commentbody" id="comment-563400">
			<cite>Jackson</cite>
						&nbsp;
			<a class="commentlink" href="#comment-563400" title="">January 25, 2011</a> 

		
			<div class="commentcount">312</div>

				<p>Well, I made this the other day, and although it turned out well, it was very laborious because of a couple mistakes I made.</p>
<p>One, I accidentally bought top-quality nibs instead of top-quality cacao powder. So, I ground up the nibs for 10, 15 minutes in the food processor, briefly worked it in a mortar and pestle (which easily separates the fat), sifted it twice, and repeated that process twice to approximate cacao powder. (Would have saved money for sure if I hadn&#8217;t done that.)</p>
<p>Two, the only raw peanuts at Whole Foods were not peeled, and I was too lazy to do it myself. So, the peanuts didn&#8217;t liquefy (or even turn into &#8216;butter&#8217; for that matter, and were somewhat grainy. I fixed this by adding in extra peanut oil, and although it is a little grainy, it tastes fine.</p>
<p>So yeah, thanks for the recipe, hopefully I can do better next time, because I don&#8217;t think this had to be so hard.</p>
	</li>
		
		
		
	
